\begin{abstract}
We formalize the Nexus Fusion Model as a nonlinear controlled dynamical
system with a triple-product threshold, local nonlinear stability,
optimal-control necessary conditions, forward invariance and reachability
of the fusion set, a bridge activation law coupling the fusion functional
to a lattice path geometry, and a verification-oriented finite-state
abstraction. Sufficient conditions for global envelope bounds in discrete
verification models are established.
\end{abstract}

%% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}
%% ============================================================

The Nexus Fusion Model is a three-state nonlinear control system with
threshold-defined operating modes. Its core performance functional is
the triple product
\[
\Phi(x)=EN\tau,
\]
where $E$ is lattice energy, $N$ is active node density, and $\tau$ is
the stability window. Fusion Mode is entered when
$\Phi(x)\ge C_{\mathrm{Nexus}}$ for a critical threshold
$C_{\mathrm{Nexus}}>0$.

This paper provides a self-contained specification of the model with
five analytical components: nonlinear dynamics and well-posedness,
stability analysis via linearization and Lyapunov theory, Pontryagin
optimal control, forward invariance and reachability of the fusion set,
a bridge activation law coupling the fusion functional to a discrete
lattice geometry, and a finite-state abstraction with soundness guarantees.

